The '''Coalition for International Justice''' (CIJ) was an international, [[non-profit]] organization based in both [[Washington D.C.]] and [[The Hague]] that supported the international [[war crimes]] [[tribunals]] for [[Rwanda]] and the former [[Yugoslavia]], and criminal and transitional justice initiatives for [[East Timor]], [[Sierra Leone]], [[Cambodia]], and [[Sudan]].  CIJ initiated and conducted advocacy and public education campaigns, targeting decision-makers in [[Washington DC|Washington]] and other capitals, media, and the public.

In the field, CIJ provided practical assistance on legal, technical, and outreach matters to the tribunals and other justice initiatives.  From 2000-2003, CIJ conducted a substantial rule of law project in East Timor.  Most recently, in July 2004, CIJ assembled an international team of professionals who conducted over 1,200 interviews in Chad with refugees who had fled the [[Darfur conflict|conflict in Darfur]], Sudan.

On March 31, 2006, the Coalition for Justice closed operations. In a letter from its board of directors, they noted that CIJ "was not intended to become a permanent institution."[http://www.cij.org/CIJ_Farewell_Letter.pdf]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}


