{{Infobox political party | name = Democratic Forum for Modernity | colorcode = Purple | foundation = 27 November 1997 | ideology = [[Liberalism]] | country = Central African Republic }} {{Politics of the Central African Republic}}
The '''Democratic Forum for Modernity''' ({{lang-fr|Forum Démocratique pour la Modernité}}, FODEM) is a [[political party]] in the [[Central African Republic]].
==History== The party was founded by [[Charles Massi]] on 27 November 1997 and legally recognized on 4 May 1998.<ref name=Pro>[http://www.fodem.org/fodem%20rca/biographie.htm Charles Massi] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927102712/http://www.fodem.org/fodem%20rca/biographie.htm |date=2007-09-27 }} FODEM</ref> In the [[Central African Republic parliamentary election, 1998|1998 parliamentary elections]] it won two seats in the [[National Assembly (Central African Republic)|National Assembly]]. Massi was the party's candidate for the [[Central African Republic presidential election, 1999|1999 presidential elections]], finishing eighth out of ten candidates with 1.3% of the vote.
In the first round of the [[Central African Republic general election, 2005|presidential elections]] held on 13 March 2005, Massi won 3.2% of the vote.<ref name=DB>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/cf.html Elections in the Central African Republic], African Elections Database.</ref> He backed [[François Bozizé]] in the second round<ref>[http://www.izf.net/izf/Actualite/RDP/04/rca.htm Elections: MM. Ngoupandé et Massi apportent leur soutien à M. Bozizé] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928021526/http://www.izf.net/izf/Actualite/RDP/04/rca.htm |date=2007-09-28 }} AFP, 21 April 2005 {{fr icon}}</ref> and became a Minister of State in the government after the elections.<ref name=List>[http://www.izf.net/izf/Guide/R%C3%A9publique%20Centrafricaine/gouvernement.htm Lists of governments of the Central African Republic] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928021935/http://www.izf.net/izf/Guide/R%C3%A9publique%20Centrafricaine/gouvernement.htm |date=2007-09-28 }} IZF {{fr icon}}</ref> In the simultaneous National Assembly elections, the party was reduced to a single seat.
After Massi was appointed as Political Coordinator of the [[Union of Democratic Forces for the Rally]] (UFDR) rebel group,<ref>[http://www.acap-cf.info/Cyriaque-Gonda-deplore-la-designation-de-Charles-Massi-comme-coordonnateur-politique-de-l-UFDR_a1170.html Cyriaque Gonda déplore la désignation de Charles Massi comme coordonnateur politique de l'UFDR] ACAP, 14 May 2008 {{fr icon}}</ref> FODEM rejected this move and expelled Massi from the party; it established a provisional political bureau on 22 May 2008 with [[Joseph Garba Ouangolé]] as President.<ref>[http://www.acap-cf.info/Bienvenu-Guinon-du-Fodem-appelle-au-patriotisme-des-Centrafricains_a1514.html Bienvenu Guinon du Fodem appelle au patriotisme des Centrafricains] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721183817/http://www.acap-cf.info/Bienvenu-Guinon-du-Fodem-appelle-au-patriotisme-des-Centrafricains_a1514.html |date=2011-07-21 }} ACAP, 2 September 2008 {{fr icon}}</ref>
In 2010 FODEM joined the Presidential Majority alliance in preparation for the [[Central African Republic general election, 2011|2011 general elections]].<ref>[http://www.journaldebangui.com/article.php?aid=565 Political agreement between the parties of the Presidential Majority] Journal de Bangui, 24 December 2010</ref> The party nominated six candidates for the 105 seats in the [[National Assembly (Central African Republic)|National Assembly]],<ref>[http://www.content.eisa.org.za/old-page/car-number-national-assembly-candidates-party-2011-election CAR: Number of National Assembly candidates by party in the 2011 election] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402135656/http://www.content.eisa.org.za/old-page/car-number-national-assembly-candidates-party-2011-election |date=April 2, 2015 }} EISA</ref> and although the alliance won 11 seats, FODEM failed to win a seat.
