{{Infobox military installation | name = Xwejni Redoubt | native_name = Ridott tax-Xwejni | location = [[Żebbuġ, Gozo|Żebbuġ]], [[Gozo]], [[Malta]] | image = | caption = | type = [[Redoubt]] | coordinates = | ownership = | controlledby = | open_to_public = | built = 1715–1716 | used = | builder = [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]] | materials = [[Limestone]] | height = | fate = Demolished | battles = | events = }}
'''Xwejni Redoubt''' ({{lang-mt|Ridott tax-Xwejni}}) was a [[redoubt]] in Xwejni Bay, limits of [[Żebbuġ, Gozo|Żebbuġ]], [[Gozo]], [[Malta]]. It was built by the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]] between 1715 and 1716 as one of a series of coastal fortifications around the coasts of the Maltese Islands.
The redoubt formed part of a chain of fortifications built to defend [[Marsalforn Bay|Marsalforn]] and nearby bays from Ottoman or Barbary attacks. Although the area was fortified by a number of [[Marsalforn Tower|towers]], batteries, redoubts and entrenchments, all of these have been destroyed except for [[Qolla l-Bajda Battery]] between [[Qbajjar]] and [[Xwejni Bay]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bezzina|first1=Joseph|title=Marsalforn Culture & History|url=http://www.zebbuggozo.com/history-marsalforn.php|website=Żebbuġ Local Council|accessdate=7 August 2015}}</ref>
Xwejni Redoubt was unusual in the sense that it had a semicircular or rectangular platform, while most redoubts were pentagonal.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Spiteri|first1=Stephen C.|title=18th Century Hospitaller Coastal Batteries|url=http://www.militaryarchitecture.com/index.php/Fortifications/18th-century-hospitaller-coastal-batteries.html|website=MilitaryArchitecture.com|accessdate=7 August 2015|date=10 April 2010}}</ref>
No remains of the redoubt have survived.<ref>{{mt icon}} {{cite journal|last1=Camilleri|first1=Alex|title=It-Toponomastika t'Għawdex: Ix-Xtut taż-Żebbuġ, l-Għasri, u l-Għarb|journal=L-Imnara|date=2009|volume=9|issue=2|page=73|url=http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/L-Imnara/L-Imnara.%2009(2009)2=33/09s.pdf|accessdate=7 August 2015|publisher=Għaqda tal-Folklor}}</ref>
